>
  <p>You already know the gap I mean. You meant to stay calm, and you snapped. You decided to speak up, and you went quiet. You promised yourself this time would be different, and somewhere in the middle you watched yourself do the exact thing you swore you'd stop doing.</p>
  <p>Most people explain this gap one of two ways: <em>something's wrong with me,</em> or <em>I just need more willpower.</em> Both are wrong, and both keep you stuck, because they aim at the wrong target.</p>
  <p>Here's what's actually happening. The behavior you can't seem to stop is doing a job. It made sense once — to a younger or more frightened or more overwhelmed version of you — and it's still running because no one ever told it the situation changed. You're not failing to control it. You're succeeding at protecting something, usually without knowing what.</p>
  <p>That's why willpower doesn't work. You can't out-muscle something that's trying to keep you safe. It will always be more motivated than you are, because it thinks the stakes are survival.</p>
  <p>So instead of fighting it, get curious about it. The next time you do the thing you didn't want to do, don't ask <em>what's wrong with me.</em> Ask three questions instead:</p>

  <h3>What was I feeling right before?</h3>
  <p>Not the surface feeling — the one underneath. Not "annoyed," but exposed. Not "fine," but quietly afraid no one was going to show up for me.</p>

  <h3>What was the behavior trying to protect me from?</h3>
  <p>Almost everything we do that frustrates us is keeping something at bay: rejection, disappointment, conflict, the risk of wanting something and not getting it.</p>

  <h3>When did this first make sense?</h3>
  <p>Not to excuse it. To date it. Most of these patterns are old, and most are solving a problem that isn't your current problem anymore.</p>

  <p>You won't always get a clean answer, and you don't need one. The point isn't to solve yourself in an afternoon. It's the shift that happens the moment you stop treating your own behavior as a defect and start treating it as information. The fight with yourself quiets down, just a little — and a little is enough to start.</p>
  <p class="lead">The thing you keep doing makes sense. Once you find out how, you finally get to do something else.</p>
</Subpage>
